1 SECTION 3. IC 21-22-6-3, AS AMENDED BY P.L.174-2018,
2 SECTION 20, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
3 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 3. The campus board consists of at least seven (7)
4 members, including the respective regional representative of the
5 state board of trustees appointed under IC 21-22-3-3, who serves
6 as a nonvoting member, and at least five (5) members who are
7 representative of the manufacturing, commercial, agricultural, labor,
8 and educational groups of the campus service area, all appointed by the
9 state board of trustees. Membership may include a representative from
10 a school corporation that has part of its district within the campus
11 service area and at least one (1) Ivy Tech Community College student
12 who is enrolled at the campus. All members of the campus board must
13 be residents of the campus service area. Appointments are for three (3)
14 year terms, on a staggered basis, and all trustees must be citizens of
15 Indiana. Members may serve for an unlimited number of terms.
16 SECTION 4. IC 21-22-6-8, AS AMENDED BY P.L.174-2018,
17 SECTION 25, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
18 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 8. A campus board shall do the following:
19 (1) Make a careful analysis of the educational needs and
20 opportunities of the campus service area, including an analysis of
21 programs and pathways designed to meet workforce and employer
22 demand.
23 (2) Develop and recommend to the state board of trustees a plan
24 for providing postsecondary:
25 (A) general education;
26 (B) liberal arts education; and
27 (C) occupational and technical education;
28 programs and appropriate workforce development, assessment,
29 and training services for the residents of that campus service area.
30 (3) Develop and recommend a budget for campus programs and
31 operations.
32 (4) Identify and recommend methods to optimize the use of
33 facilities and equipment to support programs and pathways
34 designed to meet workforce and employer demand.
35 (5) Facilitate and develop cooperation with employers,
36 community leaders, economic development efforts, area career
37 and technical education centers, and other public and private
38 education and training entities in order to provide postsecondary
39 general, liberal arts, and occupational and technical education and
40 training designed to meet workforce and employer demand in an
41 efficient and cost effective manner and to avoid duplication of
42 services.
